---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import SiteNav from '../components/SiteNav.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="About FuryStack">
  <div class="page-template">
    <div class="site-nav-main">
      <div class="inner" style="padding: 0 5vw;">
        <SiteNav />
      </div>
    </div>

    <main class="page-main">
      <div class="page-inner">
        <h1>About FuryStack</h1>
        <div class="page-content">
          <p class="lead">
            FuryStack is a flexible, end-to-end framework that allows you to build
            complex services quickly and easily.
          </p>
          <p>
            Written in TypeScript, FuryStack provides clean, readable public APIs
            built on top of native Node.js calls with carefully selected dependencies.
            You can create a backend in minutes with authentication, data stores,
            custom actions, and more &mdash; without having to search for packages
            for entry-level functionality.
          </p>
          <p>
            The framework ships with everything you need to get started: dependency
            injection, authentication, multiple data store backends (MongoDB, Redis,
            Sequelize, filesystem), entity authorization, logging, caching, and
            internationalization. If you only need a subset, every package can be
            used independently.
          </p>
          <p>
            On the frontend, FuryStack includes <strong>Shades</strong> &mdash;
            a custom JSX-based UI library with type-safe syntax and unidirectional
            data binding, plus micro-frontend support. The same concepts and design
            principles are shared between the frontend and backend: DI, logging,
            disposables, and more work in the same way and from the same packages.
          </p>
          <p>
            Type-safe REST API definitions can be shared between server and client
            in a monorepo, giving you end-to-end type checking across the full stack.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </main>

    <Footer />
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .page-template { display: flex; flex-direction: column; min-height: 100vh; }

  .page-main {
    flex-grow: 1;
    padding: calc(64px + 48px) 5vw 80px;
    background: #fff;
  }
  @media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) { .page-main { background: var(--color-darkmode); } }

  .page-inner {
    max-width: 720px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  .page-inner h1 {
    margin-bottom: 32px;
    font-size: 3.6rem;
    letter-spacing: -0.03em;
  }
  @media (max-width: 600px) { .page-inner h1 { font-size: 2.6rem; } }

  .page-content {
    font-size: 1.8rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: var(--color-body);
  }
  @media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) { .page-content { color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.72); } }

  .lead {
    font-size: 2.1rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--color-darkgrey);
    line-height: 1.5;
  }
  @media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) { .lead { color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.85); } }
</style>
